	<h1>Know Your Rights</h1>
	<br />
	<h2>1. Know Your Rights<br />
	2. Way To Heal<br />
	3. How to File A Complaint</h2>
	Birthing practices around the world are changing. As women become more
	educated about their bodies, their babies and birthing and as they
	become more aware of their rights as a consumer and as a respected
	person in society, they are demanding change. <br />
	<br />
	Despite this, many women still do not feel comfortable or capable of
	voicing their concerns or complaints, thinking it is impossible, too
	hard or not within their rights to challenge or question a doctor.
	Additionally many women feel and are told that if their baby is healthy
	then the way they were treated is justified.<br />
	<br />
	How a woman is treated in birth is important to her and her baby as how
	she feels directly impacts her ability to mother well. Medical
	negligence, lack of informed consent and rape in birth is often in the
	form of: <br />
	<br />
	1. Incorrect diagnosis of an emergency, leading to unnecessary medical
	interventions or caesarean surgery. <br />
	2. A fabrication of an emergency by incorrect use of technology and a
	language of fear. <br />
	3. Treatment given without informed consent, omission of information,
	over-riding a refusal of treatment, misrepresentation of a medical
	situation. While the majority of courts have held that the state may not
	force women to undergo unwanted cesareans many women continue to find
	that they are pressured or coerced into such procedures, or they find
	that no health care provider will support their decision to have a
	vaginal birth after a c-section ("VBAC"). Additionally often it is not
	made clear which birthing practices a doctor follows, thus it is
	difficult for women to correctly choose the doctor which suits their
	birth beliefs. Worst still some may listen and agree and accept a
	woman’s birth plans but do something very different at the time of
	birth.<br />
	4. Rude, abusive or violent treatment. Abusive behavior toward women,
	especially in childbirth, is unacceptable and harmful. Includes threats,
	scolding, slapping and hitting, being tied down or forced to lie down,
	coercion, yelling, belittling, lying, manipulating, mocking, dismissing,
	refusing to acknowledge, It is known as Birth Rape! It is your right to
	give birth with dignity and respect. <br/><a
