	<h2>2. WAYS TO HEAL.</h2>
	<b>1. Join a support network.</b> We do not have a birth trauma support
	network in Mumbai at present but it only takes a few to start this.
	There are many blogs and WEB based support services. <br />
	<br />
	<a href="www.Tabs.org.nz">www.Tabs.org.nz</a> - Dealing with trauma,
	post natal depression and birth stress <br />
	<a href="http://www.birthtraumaassociation.org.uk">http://www.birthtraumaassociation.org.uk</a><br />
	<br />
	<b> 2. Write your birth story</b> – This is beneficial for three reasons
	<br />
	A. As a healing process for women who fell traumatized by their birth
	experiences, often unraveling the truth can be very healing. <br />
	B. To educate others. <br />
	C. To affect changes in maternity services and law at the government
	level. <br />
	D. Birth stories can be used in a court of law if you wish to proceed
	with a suit. <br />
	<br />
	A. Post your story on blogs – send it to your friends, get it published
	in news papers or magazines. Send it to you doctor and hospital, your
	local MP or human rights/ consumer rights lobbying groups. <br />
	Find the contact information for your state medical board (name may
	vary) and send it to them. (See contact below). <br />
	<br />
	B. Birth stories have become an important tool in birth education. They
	are a form of opening up an honest dialogue and thus we become more
	comfortable with the language of birth and the reality of birth. Very
	few urban women today understand what real birth looks like. Much of our
	understanding of birth comes from the media where it is presented as
	either comedy or high emergency drama and society and families mostly
	remain hush hush about the event. Seeing real birth and hearing the real
	stories of birth helps us to birth naturally - without that we are
	fearful and easily manipulated at our most vulnerable moment in life –as
	they say Knowledge is power! <br />
	<br />
	C. Birth stories are also political. Many women write of their
	experiences and send it to their local MP. The more women do this the
	more likely state level policies in maternity care will change. <br />
	<br />
	D. Dated personal hand written narrative can be used in court. Have your
	statement notarized by a public notary. Ask anyone else who witnessed
	the events to do the same – write it down, sign and date it. Collective
	action – if other women have experienced the same make a complaint
	together. In birth stories incorporate, medical facts and statistics.
	Back up evidence with your surgical report (all hospitals must hand this
	over - all it takes is a letter of request). <br />
	Find the “consumers” or “complaints” or “patients rights” whom can give
	you information on how to file a complaint. <br />
	Also find the states medical practice act and the professional code of
	conduct and the Obstetricians & Gynecologists ethics statement this will
	help you to determine where you medical providers broke laws and codes
	of practice. Lodge a complaint with the doctors Registration body,
	Indian medical council, or your local medical council <br /><br/>
